What's going to happen?

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:07.880
What's going to happen?

00:02:07.880 --> 00:02:14.960
And wait for it.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:17.640
Yeah, we got him!

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:18.120
Yeah!

00:02:18.120 --> 00:02:21.500
So that MP4 file I found on the ground turned out

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.100
to be my glorious victory over Trabio.

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:26.720
So how do I know that?

00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:29.260
How do I know it's Eli's livestream that happened there

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:29.480
?

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:35.160
And that has to do with Streamplace's signing format.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.680
So we needed to...

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:41.190
So decentralized VOD is something that's kind of existed before

00:02:41.190 --> 00:02:41.720
, right?

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:42.840
You could argue...

00:02:42.840 --> 00:02:43.780
This will be a popular opinion.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:46.720
You could argue video NFTs are kind of like a decentralized

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:47.400
VOD, right?

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:49.930
Where you've got an IPFS reference to something that's

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:52.260
, like, out there and not controlled by any one party

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:54.300
, lots of other, like, IPFS-based,

00:02:54.550 --> 00:02:56.490
like, there's, like, DAT-based live

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:59.500
streaming that maybe falls into that.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.100
But for the most part, we needed to invent what a

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:02.260
decentralized live stream is.

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:05.840
So what we did was we took the first thing that happens

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:09.760
is you generate a signing key, same as the kind that

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:12.250
's used to secure your app proto repository.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:15.980
We then take that signing key.

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:19.500
You then configure your OBS instance, just like we're

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:22.440
doing here, to stream in to Streamplace.

00:03:22.440 --> 00:03:25.310
You actually provide it with that signing key, so it has

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:26.980
the capability of signing on your behalf.

00:03:26.980 --> 00:03:29.510
If you really care about your key custody, you should run

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:31.970
Streamplace locally and then syndicate it out to a server

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:32.120
.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:36.810
Then this is basically every live stream you've ever watched,

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:40.170
if you haven't messed with video infrastructure before, is just

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:43.860
a bunch of short video files that are thrown into your face

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:46.150
in sequence, and it provides the illusion of a live stream

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:46.360
.

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:47.720
So that's how we do it.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:50.280
Each MP4 file comes in.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:54.690
We give each one of them an embedded signature using technology from

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:57.200
the C2PA, the Coalition for Content Provenance

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:58.080
and Authenticity.

00:03:58.980 --> 00:03:59.880
Cool format.

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:03.400
It provides a mechanism for giving you an MP4 file that

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:07.950
contains an embedded signature over a hash of all of that MP

00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:11.060
4 file except for that part of the signature.

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:12.880
That's really tricky to get right, and that's one

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:14.940
of the things I really like about the C2PA's

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:19.800
tooling is you've got this, a lot of decentralized media

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:24.860
projects have external signatures, so you might have, this actually

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:26.640
included like blue sky videos, right?

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:28.200
How do you know it's my blue sky video?

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:31.780
It's because there's a blob out there that is referenced

00:04:32.020 --> 00:04:35.830
by a record in my repository, and my repository has a

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:37.470
signature on the root commit, so that's how you know

00:04:37.470 --> 00:04:38.280
it's mine, right?

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:41.380
What I like about this format is I can have, this

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:44.500
is the MP4 file on the ground example I just gave

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:44.780
, right?

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:47.270
You can have arbitrary MP4 file on your computer, and

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:50.030
all of that signing and provenance data is intact and embedded

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:50.980
in the MP4 file.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:52.480
So I like that a lot.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:56.820
It's something we really wanted to preserve as we moved from

00:04:56.820 --> 00:05:00.020
live to VOD, and lots of very cool metadata in

00:05:00.020 --> 00:05:00.460
here.

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:02.520
We're not doing too much with this mechanism yet.

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:05.900
I spent a long time talking to Trezzy yesterday about

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:07.280
embedding this.

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:09.570
Part of the embedded metadata here should be that I'm playing

00:05:09.570 --> 00:05:10.460
Silksong, right?

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:12.560
And then if you care about Silksong, you can

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:15.740
watch that livestream and get that data from from, like,

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:17.420
pretty much any direction, right?

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.530
Like, you can download it from sketchiest website in the

00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:21.000
world.

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:23.270
ru and still be confident that you're looking at the right

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:23.880
thing, right?

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:26.040
And then I'm playing Silksong.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:29.970
Those, yeah, that's this example.

00:05:29.980 --> 00:05:32.380
I have, yeah, we've made StreamPlace as

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:34.920
easy to run as possible, so you can run your own

00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:37.680
StreamPlace node, syndicate my streams, they get

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:40.440
copied over in this sort of trustless, unauthent

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:42.460
icated way, and then you see it over there.

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:46.760
So the thinking here is we probably won't beat Twitch by

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:51.000
making a bigger data center or buying more bandwidth than Amazon,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.670
but we might be able to beat them by following the example

00:05:53.850 --> 00:05:54.780
of BitTorrent, right?

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:58.290
That you can have lots of decentralized infrastructure that's replicating

00:05:58.290 --> 00:06:00.740
all of this, but through the magic of digital signatures,

00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:02.560
you know that the video is authentic.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:04.900
So what's the problem?

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:07.920
This isn't very convenient.

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:11.050
So when I say slice the video up into one-second

00:06:11.050 --> 00:06:13.420
MP4 files, I'm being very literal about that.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:15.650
If you run StreamPlace on your computer, you can

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:18.290
navigate to this and see lots and lots and lots of one

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:19.800
-second MP4 files.

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:21.750
And when the computer is processing them all and feeding to you

00:06:21.750 --> 00:06:22.920
as a live stream, that's okay.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.130
Afterward, when you want to work with this as a

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:26.500
VOD, it's a pain in the ass.

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:30.860
So we wanted, this was one of the design goals of

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:34.330
VOD for us, is how do we handle that?

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:37.720
And unfortunately, because we used regular MP4 files, they

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:39.280
're non-concatenatable.

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:42.040
You can't take two MP4 files, squish all the

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:45.180
bytes together, and get valid output, right?

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:47.320
That's just not, now MP4 works.

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:48.900
It's not valid data there.

00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:51.760
So you'd have to mux it, and the signature

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.280
that you get there wouldn't match the input, and all

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:57.330
of a sudden you've broken this entire cool BitTor

00:06:57.330 --> 00:06:59.580
rent-y provenance mechanism that I was just describing.

00:06:59.580 --> 00:07:06.430
So this is the other reason we were already looking at for

00:07:06.430 --> 00:07:08.400
king C2PA.

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:12.620
So here we have a list of signing algorithms.

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:19.160
As you can see here, we have the good and virtuous

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:24.930
EC-DSA signature over a SHA-256 hash

00:07:24.930 --> 00:07:29.930
, over the P-256 curve, but not over

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:34.360
the SCCP-256-K1 curve, the

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:38.350
evil, shady curve that's used inside BitTorrent

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:40.000
and Ethereum and AppRoto, right?

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.860
So I think my theory here is that somebody in Adobe had

00:07:44.860 --> 00:07:49.120
to sell their, some exec that they weren't making blockchain

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:49.760
software here.

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:51.660
So we didn't do that kind of signing.

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:52.780
We only did this kind of signing.

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:55.410
So technically, for as long as StreamPlace has existed

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:57.520
, it hasn't been C2PA compatible, and I

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:59.860
had been looking for a while to formalize that.

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:03.140
So, oh yeah, this is the other.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:06.720
So this is the other.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:12.390
So Adobe's out there right now lobbying, especially European governments

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:17.490
and the state of California to require provenance data on everything

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:20.040
that you post on social media.

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:22.160
This is the reason for the C2PA's existence,

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:24.340
getting us ready for a world filled with deep fakes.

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.520
This is not inherently a bad idea.

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:29.860
You know, once anybody can deep fake anything, how do

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:32.400
you ever trust what you're looking at?

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:34.920
No one technical mechanism can solve that problem.

00:08:34.920 --> 00:08:37.870
But one way you could be more confident is if there was

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:40.680
provenance data embedded in the live stream, right?

00:08:40.680 --> 00:08:42.580
Where it says, oh, this video was taken from Eli

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:45.490
's camera and then edited using this software and makes its way

00:08:45.490 --> 00:08:47.020
everywhere, right?

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:49.830
But the reason Adobe's doing this lobbying is because they want

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:51.920
to try and do some regulatory capture, right?

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:56.120
So they want to sell governments these expensive Creative Cloud subscriptions and

00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:59.570
be like the only software that you could possibly use in order

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:00.740
to do all of that stuff.

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:04.780
Also, the part I think is really funny is they want

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:07.300
you to go pay like a CA, like $107

00:09:07.300 --> 00:09:08.780
a month for a signing certificate.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:11.980
Like, let's encrypt and everything never happened.

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:14.840
And, of course, like the App Proto and decentralized

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:17.600
web communities, we have, you know, dids and

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:20.750
totally other stacks of how we would handle some of this stuff

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:21.250
, right?

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:25.990
How we would handle key custody, how we would handle authenticity

00:09:25.990 --> 00:09:27.080
, that kind of thing.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.230
PLC directories got its own, got its own sort

00:09:29.230 --> 00:09:30.460
of take on everything.

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:35.180
So, yeah, some good ideas needs to be modernized

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:39.340
and not try and pay these vendors a bunch of money for

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:39.940
certificates.

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:43.590
So, I said all of these things out loud a lot

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:48.090
and the folks, the good folks at the IPFS Foundation

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:50.300
and the Dazzle Project were very, very receptive to

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:50.600
it.

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:53.710
So, they've given us a grant, everything you see

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:57.090
so far, everything you see past this point in the presentation

00:09:57.090 --> 00:09:59.510
is a result of the grant that we got from the IP

00:09:59.510 --> 00:10:00.580
FS Foundation.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:04.180
So, we're working on two specs with them, St

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:05.690
upa and Muxle.

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:10.600
Stupa is the simple standard for provenance and authenticity.

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:12.440
This is the simpler of the two standards.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.200
It's very much, thank you, Ted.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:15.480
Look at that.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:16.620
Ted got me a glass of water.

00:10:16.620 --> 00:10:17.420
Everybody thank Ted.

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:18.320
That was awesome.

00:10:20.860 --> 00:10:24.460
Stupa is our, I don't know what makes a

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:29.440
fork a hostile fork, but it's definitely a fork of

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:32.520
the C2PA that takes out all the things.

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:34.080
It actually doesn't take out anything.

00:10:34.080 --> 00:10:35.570
Like, if you want to pay DigiCert 200

00:10:35.570 --> 00:10:36.860
bucks a month, you totally can.

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:39.820
But we have some different opinions about that.

00:10:39.820 --> 00:10:40.700
We have dids, right?

00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:44.420
So, instead of signing it with some cert that you're

00:10:44.680 --> 00:10:47.350
given by a CA, you sign it with a signing key

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:50.700
that has a provenance chain back to your at proto identity

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:52.200
, right?

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:55.560
And then we also, like, make it consistent with D

00:10:55.760 --> 00:10:56.140
azzle.

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:59.500
The C2PA signatures, C2PA manifests, rather

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.200
, already use C-Bore.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:03.880
So, we're just upgrading it to use Drizzle.

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:06.480
Drizzle, Dazzle's, a very strict subset

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:08.880
of C-Bore used in at proto, right?

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:10.680
That's Stupa.

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:11.320
That's all of Stupa.

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:12.710
The rest of the presentation is about Muxle because it

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:13.520
's way more complicated.

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:16.280
This is just a little change that we're making here.

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:17.940
Would love if they upstreamed it.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:22.850
Would love if there were dids and K256 signing

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:24.160
in C2PA.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:27.760
So, let's talk about the design goals for Mux

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:28.400
le.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:32.440
This is basically, what changes do we need to make to

00:11:32.650 --> 00:11:35.540
those MP4 files that I described before in order to make

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:37.560
them appropriate for VOD?

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:39.640
So, you don't have thousands and thousands of MP4

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:42.280
files on your computer after a long live stream.

00:11:42.280 --> 00:11:45.420
So, we want to keep the property that they're self

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:46.320
-certifying.

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:49.320
It's awesome that you can just find one of these files

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:51.300
and then go verify its provenance chain.

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:54.300
You shouldn't require external data, right?

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:57.660
As a design goal, we want to support live stream to

00:11:57.670 --> 00:12:00.660
VOD, what video engineers call DVR.

00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:03.080
Basically, if you're watching a live stream, that you

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:05.290
can seek back and see what happened one minute ago, two

00:12:05.290 --> 00:12:07.160
minutes ago, three minutes ago, that kind of thing.

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:09.680
It would be nice if it's a useful format.

00:12:09.680 --> 00:12:11.560
I don't want to give you some opaque C-B

00:12:11.560 --> 00:12:12.860
ore blob or something.

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:15.330
A design goal of this is that at the end of it

00:12:15.330 --> 00:12:17.010
, you have, at the end of a 24-hour

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:19.530
live stream, you should have a 24-hour MP4

00:12:19.530 --> 00:12:20.760
file on your computer.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:23.840
Easiest to work with, maximally compatible, preserves

00:12:23.870 --> 00:12:26.300
all of the provenance information I was describing.

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:29.840
And it should be streamable with minimal overhead.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.600
I'm not going to get too deep into media over quick

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:36.590
