00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:00.940
Fundamentally, the reason being that if the output is

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:03.230
going to be just an MP4 file on your computer,

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:06.330
that is completely different than the format that media over quick uses

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:08.990
that's going to be useful for sending things to users,

00:13:08.990 --> 00:13:11.600
in particular with things like multiple tracks, right?

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:14.760
We really want to do multi-track video, multi-

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:18.650
track audio, 720p, a bunch of other 1080p

00:13:18.730 --> 00:13:21.840
, different audio formats, AAC and Opus for different

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:22.380
things.

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:24.820
All of that complexity, we would like to be able to

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:28.400
package in this one file and that skyrockets the bandwidth

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:30.650
that you would use to send it out to people, right

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:30.900
?

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:32.240
You don't want to send them every rendition, you

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:33.140
want to send them just one.

00:13:33.140 --> 00:13:36.520
So, how do we get around that?

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:38.620
And the answer is we mux.

00:13:38.620 --> 00:13:41.200
