00:26:21.980 --> 00:26:35.320
The big alternative

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:38.400
, YMP4, there's a couple of reasons.

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:42.360
One, because it's the most ubiquitous media format,

00:26:42.570 --> 00:26:47.570
and that's the most highly compatible across everything, the second

00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:51.640
is, it gives us the media overquick stuff,

00:26:51.640 --> 00:26:53.800
tends to support it a lot already.

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:56.830
Also, the FM, so this is like CMAF

00:26:56.910 --> 00:27:00.280
, back to this thing, this is like CMAF

00:27:00.280 --> 00:27:04.170
MP4 playback, and the advantage here is it lets you

00:27:04.170 --> 00:27:07.720
separate out, it gives you that lack of redundancy that

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:10.120
I was describing where the init segment isn't, there are

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:12.480
other formats that embed all of that init data in every segment

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:14.500
, but we don't actually want that because it's redundant

00:27:14.700 --> 00:27:17.760
for a long video, so, yeah, those reasons.

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:22.030
The question was, why H.

00:27:22.030 --> 00:27:28.890
264 instead of, like, VP9 or AV1

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:29.700
?

00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:32.640
No reason other than maximum compatibility right now.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:36.230
We really, really want AV1 in StreamPlace.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:39.130
We fully intend to support AV1 as much as we do

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:39.410
H.

00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:42.490
264, especially when we do stuff like, I want

00:27:42.490 --> 00:27:44.850
StreamPlace to do a lot of things that no other

00:27:45.280 --> 00:27:48.460
streaming platforms do, like, for example, like, 4

00:27:48.460 --> 00:27:52.180
K, 120 FPS AV1 video would be so sick.

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:53.720
Can't even do it, I've tried to do it

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:54.140
with H.

00:27:54.140 --> 00:27:56.440
264, it just, like, doesn't, no

00:27:56.440 --> 00:27:59.870
encoder can even come close to handling that, so,

00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:01.910
yeah, yeah, in terms of codec support, we

00:28:01.910 --> 00:28:03.500
want to support, like, every codec that it makes

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:03.920
sense to.

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:06.010
We just started with this because we're not quite in a

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:08.750
world where I could probably get away with AV1 only,

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:10.480
and we would have needed an H.

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:13.540
264 backup anyway, in that context, that's why

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:14.230
we started with H.

00:28:14.230 --> 00:28:16.300
264, but, yeah, definitely want to support lots

00:28:16.300 --> 00:28:16.580
of codec.

